1
00:02:05,840 --> 00:02:06,840
<i>All right, team,</i>

2
00:02:06,920 --> 00:02:08,036
<i>stay in sight of each other.</i>

3
00:02:08,160 --> 00:02:09,230
<i>Let's make NASA proud today.</i>

4
00:02:10,680 --> 00:02:12,399
<i>How's it looking
over there, Watney?</i>

5
00:02:12,480 --> 00:02:13,914
<i>Well, you'll be happy to hear...</i>

6
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:16,720
<i>that in Grid Section 14-28,</i>

7
00:02:16,800 --> 00:02:19,713
<i>the particles were
predominantly coarse...</i>

8
00:02:19,800 --> 00:02:22,998
but in 29, they're much finer...

9
00:02:23,200 --> 00:02:25,112
and they should be ideal
for chem analysis.

10
00:02:25,280 --> 00:02:26,555
<i>Oh, wow.
Did everybody hear that?</i>

11
00:02:26,640 --> 00:02:28,438
<i>Markjust discovered dirt.</i>

12
00:02:28,600 --> 00:02:29,636
<i>Should we alert the media?</i>

13
00:02:29,800 --> 00:02:31,632
<i>Sorry, what are you
doing today, Martinez?</i>

14
00:02:31,800 --> 00:02:33,678
Making sure the MAV
is still upright?

15
00:02:33,760 --> 00:02:34,796
<i>I'd like you to know</i>

16
00:02:34,880 --> 00:02:35,916
<i>that visual inspection
of the equipment...</i>

17
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:37,593
<i>is imperative
to mission success.</i>

18
00:02:37,680 --> 00:02:40,514
<i>I also would like to report
that the MAV is still upright.</i>

19
00:02:40,720 --> 00:02:41,836
<i>Watney,</i>

20
00:02:41,920 --> 00:02:43,149
<i>you keep leaving
your channel open...</i>

21
00:02:43,240 --> 00:02:45,038
<i>which leads to
Martinez responding...</i>

22
00:02:45,200 --> 00:02:46,429
<i>which leads to
all of us listening...</i>

23
00:02:46,640 --> 00:02:47,790
<i>which leads to me being annoyed.</i>

24
00:02:48,400 --> 00:02:49,470
<i>Roger that.</i>

25
00:02:49,560 --> 00:02:50,835
<i>Martinez, the captain
would like you to please...</i>

26
00:02:51,000 --> 00:02:52,229
shut your smart mouth.

27
00:02:53,720 --> 00:02:55,200
We'd prefer to use
a different adjective

28
00:02:55,320 --> 00:02:56,959
to describe Martinez's mouth.

29
00:02:57,400 --> 00:02:58,754
<i>Did Beck just insult me?</i>

30
00:02:58,920 --> 00:03:00,912
<i>"Dr. Beck." And yes.</i>

31
00:03:01,080 --> 00:03:03,595
Happy to turn the radios off
from here, Commander.

32
00:03:03,760 --> 00:03:04,830
Just say the word.

33
00:03:05,000 --> 00:03:06,195
Wait, Johanssen.

34
00:03:06,280 --> 00:03:07,555
Constant communication
is the hallmark...

35
00:03:07,720 --> 00:03:08,756
Shut 'em off.

36
00:03:08,920 --> 00:03:09,990
<i>No.</i>

37
00:03:10,160 --> 00:03:11,310
No. Excuse me.

38
00:03:12,280 --> 00:03:14,237
<i>I apologize
for my countrymen, Vogel.</i>

39
00:03:14,480 --> 00:03:15,675
Accepted.

40
00:03:15,880 --> 00:03:17,837
How many samples
do we need, Commander?

41
00:03:18,040 --> 00:03:19,040
<i>Seven.</i>

42
00:03:19,520 --> 00:03:20,636
<i>100 grams each.</i>

43
00:03:27,000 --> 00:03:28,912
We have a mission update.
A storm warning.

44
00:03:29,080 --> 00:03:30,560
<i>Commander,
you should come inside.</i>

45
00:03:30,640 --> 00:03:31,915
<i>You're gonna want to see this.</i>

46
00:03:32,080 --> 00:03:33,080
What is it?

47
00:03:33,160 --> 00:03:34,196
<i>A storm warning.</i>

48
00:03:34,400 --> 00:03:35,720
I saw that
in this morning's briefing.

49
00:03:35,880 --> 00:03:37,758
We'll be inside before it hits.

50
00:03:37,920 --> 00:03:40,640
Yeah, they upgraded
their estimate.

51
00:03:40,800 --> 00:03:42,439
The storm's gonna be
a lot worse.

52
00:03:48,920 --> 00:03:51,071
<i>Martinez, how does it look?</i>

53
00:03:52,200 --> 00:03:53,270
<i>Not good.</i>

54
00:03:56,160 --> 00:03:59,119
"1,200 kilometers in diameter,
bearing 24.41 degrees."

55
00:03:59,280 --> 00:04:00,430
That's tracking
right towards us.

56
00:04:00,600 --> 00:04:02,000
"Based on current escalation,

57
00:04:02,080 --> 00:04:04,436
"estimated force
of 8,600 newtons."

58
00:04:05,360 --> 00:04:06,635
What's the abort force?

59
00:04:06,800 --> 00:04:08,439
7,500.

60
00:04:09,320 --> 00:04:11,596
<i>Anything more than
that and the MAV could tip.</i>

61
00:04:11,760 --> 00:04:13,035
Do we scrub?

62
00:04:13,200 --> 00:04:14,429
Begin abort procedure.

63
00:04:14,960 --> 00:04:17,236
We are estimating
with a margin of error.

64
00:04:17,440 --> 00:04:18,999
We could wait it out.

65
00:04:19,360 --> 00:04:20,840
Let's wait it out.

66
00:04:22,480 --> 00:04:23,675
Let's wait it out.

67
00:04:25,280 --> 00:04:26,714
Commander?

68
00:04:27,400 --> 00:04:28,675
Prep emergency departure.

69
00:04:28,840 --> 00:04:30,115
Commander?

70
00:04:30,280 --> 00:04:32,192
We're scrubbed.
That's an order.

71
00:04:42,760 --> 00:04:45,275
<i>Martinez,
how long before take-off?</i>

72
00:04:45,440 --> 00:04:46,476
12 minutes.

73
00:04:49,760 --> 00:04:51,399
Visibility is almost zero.

74
00:04:51,600 --> 00:04:52,600
Anyone gets lost,

75
00:04:52,680 --> 00:04:53,875
hone in on my suit's telemetry.

76
00:04:54,040 --> 00:04:55,040
You ready?

77
00:04:55,120 --> 00:04:56,395
Ready.

78
00:04:58,840 --> 00:05:00,194
Commander, are you okay?

79
00:05:00,320 --> 00:05:01,595
I'm okay.

80
00:05:25,880 --> 00:05:27,234
Commander, we're at 10 degrees,

81
00:05:27,320 --> 00:05:28,800
and the MAV
is gonna tip at 12.3.

82
00:05:29,400 --> 00:05:32,279
Hey! We might be able
to keep the MAV from tipping.

83
00:05:32,360 --> 00:05:33,396
How?

84
00:05:34,120 --> 00:05:37,113
Use the cables from the comms
mast as guy-lines...

85
00:05:37,280 --> 00:05:38,953
anchor it with the Rover's.

86
00:05:39,280 --> 00:05:40,350
Watch out!

87
00:05:43,600 --> 00:05:44,600
Watney!

88
00:05:46,280 --> 00:05:48,636
<i>Warning. Suit breach detected.</i>

89
00:05:48,760 --> 00:05:49,760
What happened?

90
00:05:49,800 --> 00:05:50,800
He was hit.

91
00:05:50,960 --> 00:05:51,960
Watney, report.

92
00:05:52,760 --> 00:05:53,760
Before we lost telemetry,

93
00:05:53,840 --> 00:05:54,876
his decompression alarm
went off.

94
00:05:55,040 --> 00:05:56,076
Where did you last see him?

95
00:05:56,160 --> 00:05:57,230
I don't know where he is.

96
00:05:57,320 --> 00:05:58,320
What are the vitals on his suit?

97
00:05:58,400 --> 00:05:59,400
He's offline.

98
00:05:59,480 --> 00:06:00,914
A complete loss
of signal on Watney.

99
00:06:01,080 --> 00:06:02,196
Beck!
Yeah.

100
00:06:02,360 --> 00:06:04,591
How long can he survive
decompression?

101
00:06:04,840 --> 00:06:06,069
Less than a minute.

102
00:06:06,520 --> 00:06:08,716
Line up, walk west.

103
00:06:08,880 --> 00:06:10,837
He may be prone.
We don't wanna step over him.

104
00:06:12,680 --> 00:06:13,875
Commander...

105
00:06:14,040 --> 00:06:15,679
We're at 10.5 degrees.

106
00:06:15,760 --> 00:06:16,910
<i>Warning. Excessive tilt.</i>

107
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:19,799
Tilting to 11
with all the gusts of wind.

108
00:06:20,080 --> 00:06:21,309
Copy that.

109
00:06:21,520 --> 00:06:23,876
Everyone, hone in
on Martinez's suit.

110
00:06:24,040 --> 00:06:26,077
It'll get you to airlock.
Get in, prep for launch.

111
00:06:26,400 --> 00:06:27,754
What about you, Commander?

112
00:06:27,920 --> 00:06:30,594
I'm gonna search
a little longer. Get moving!

113
00:06:30,920 --> 00:06:31,920
Go!

114
00:06:35,680 --> 00:06:36,796
Watney!

115
00:06:37,360 --> 00:06:38,953
Watney, report!

116
00:06:39,120 --> 00:06:41,157
<i>The MAV's
at 11. 6 degrees.</i>

117
00:06:41,800 --> 00:06:43,200
One good gust and we're tipping.

118
00:06:43,360 --> 00:06:44,555
If it tips, you launch.

119
00:06:44,720 --> 00:06:46,074
You really think
I'm gonna leave you behind?

120
00:06:46,240 --> 00:06:47,799
<i>That's an order, Martinez.</i>

121
00:06:48,600 --> 00:06:50,432
Mark!

122
00:06:50,720 --> 00:06:53,758
Mark! Can you hear me?

123
00:06:55,280 --> 00:06:58,034
Martinez, what about
the proximity radar?

124
00:06:58,200 --> 00:06:59,873
Could that detect Watney's suit?

125
00:07:00,040 --> 00:07:01,360
It's made to see
the <i>Hermes</i> from orbit...

126
00:07:01,560 --> 00:07:03,438
not a little piece of metal
from a single suit.

127
00:07:03,600 --> 00:07:04,600
<i>Give it a try.</i>

128
00:07:04,680 --> 00:07:05,680
Roger.

129
00:07:05,920 --> 00:07:06,920
What is she thinking?
She knows

130
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:08,116
the infrared can't
get through a sandstorm.

131
00:07:08,320 --> 00:07:10,437
She's grasping for anything.

132
00:07:10,600 --> 00:07:11,600
<i>We've got negative contact</i>

133
00:07:11,680 --> 00:07:12,750
<i>on the proximity radar.</i>

134
00:07:12,880 --> 00:07:13,880
Nothing?

135
00:07:14,040 --> 00:07:15,997
<i>No.
I can barely see the Hab.</i>

136
00:07:17,160 --> 00:07:19,277
Commander, I know you don't
wanna hear this, but...

137
00:07:19,440 --> 00:07:20,510
Mark is dead.

138
00:07:22,040 --> 00:07:23,360
<i>Commander!</i>

139
00:07:23,520 --> 00:07:26,035
Hey, what the hell
is wrong with you, man?

140
00:07:26,200 --> 00:07:27,200
My friend just died.

141
00:07:27,280 --> 00:07:28,475
I don't want
my commander to die, too.

142
00:07:28,640 --> 00:07:29,869
<i>Stability warning.</i>

143
00:07:30,080 --> 00:07:31,116
We're tipping!

144
00:07:31,280 --> 00:07:34,557
<i>Commander, you need
to get back to the ship, now!</i>

145
00:07:34,680 --> 00:07:35,680
13 degrees.

146
00:07:36,640 --> 00:07:38,120
If we pass balance,
we'll never rock back.

147
00:07:38,280 --> 00:07:39,509
I've got one more trick left,

148
00:07:39,600 --> 00:07:41,034
and then I'm following orders,
Commander.

149
00:07:42,920 --> 00:07:44,400
You're firing the OMS?

150
00:07:45,040 --> 00:07:46,040
That's right.

151
00:07:50,080 --> 00:07:51,150
Commander!

152
00:07:51,760 --> 00:07:53,035
On my way.

153
00:07:56,440 --> 00:07:57,635
<i>Johanssen, let's go.</i>

154
00:08:05,200 --> 00:08:07,237
Mark!

155
00:08:19,360 --> 00:08:20,840
<i>We're at 11.5
and holding.</i>

156
00:08:24,560 --> 00:08:25,596
<i>Ready to go on your command.</i>

157
00:08:28,040 --> 00:08:29,110
Ready to launch.

158
00:08:30,400 --> 00:08:31,629
Commander.

159
00:08:31,960 --> 00:08:33,633
I need you to verbally tell me
whether or not to.

160
00:08:33,800 --> 00:08:34,870
Launch.

161
00:09:16,480 --> 00:09:18,073
<i>At around 4:30 a.m.</i>

162
00:09:18,200 --> 00:09:19,634
<i>Central Standard Time...</i>

163
00:09:19,800 --> 00:09:21,871
<i>our satellites detected a storm</i>

164
00:09:21,960 --> 00:09:24,475
<i>approaching the</i> Ares 3
<i>mission site on Mars.</i>

165
00:09:24,960 --> 00:09:28,476
<i>At 6:45, the storm
had escalated to severe...</i>

166
00:09:28,640 --> 00:09:31,519
<i>and we had no choice
but to abort the mission.</i>

167
00:09:31,680 --> 00:09:34,070
<i>Thanks to the quick action
of Commander Lewis...</i>

168
00:09:34,240 --> 00:09:37,358
<i>astronauts Beck, Johanssen,
Martinez and Vogel...</i>

169
00:09:37,520 --> 00:09:40,240
<i>were all able to reach
the Mars Ascent Vehicle...</i>

170
00:09:40,400 --> 00:09:43,837
<i>and perform an emergency
launch at 7:28 Central Time.</i>

171
00:09:45,400 --> 00:09:47,596
Unfortunately,
during the evacuation...

172
00:09:47,760 --> 00:09:51,754
astronaut Mark Watney was
struck by debris and killed.

173
00:09:53,000 --> 00:09:54,878
Commander Lewis
and the rest of her team...

174
00:09:55,040 --> 00:09:57,509
were able to intercept safely
with the <i>Hermes</i>

175
00:09:57,600 --> 00:09:59,671
and are now heading home.

176
00:09:59,840 --> 00:10:02,275
But Mark Watney is dead.

177
00:10:02,520 --> 00:10:03,556
Director Sanders!

178
00:10:38,040 --> 00:10:40,430
<i>Oxygen level critical.</i>

179
00:10:47,000 --> 00:10:49,071
<i>Oxygen level critical.</i>

180
00:10:55,920 --> 00:10:57,559
<i>Oxygen level...</i>

181
00:12:15,640 --> 00:12:17,871
<i>Pressure stable.</i>

182
00:15:17,680 --> 00:15:19,000
Fuck.

183
00:15:48,560 --> 00:15:49,560
Okay.

184
00:15:49,960 --> 00:15:51,030
<i>Okay.</i>

185
00:15:53,040 --> 00:15:57,080
<i>Hello, this is Mark Watney,
astronaut.</i>

186
00:15:57,800 --> 00:16:00,634
<i>I'm entering this log
for the record...</i>

187
00:16:01,200 --> 00:16:03,556
<i>in case I don't make it.</i>

188
00:16:06,200 --> 00:16:10,274
<i>It is 06:53 on Sol 19...</i>

189
00:16:10,440 --> 00:16:13,274
<i>and I'm alive.</i>

190
00:16:14,600 --> 00:16:15,716
<i>Obviously.</i>

191
00:16:15,880 --> 00:16:18,440
<i>But I'm guessing that's gonna
come as a surprise</i>

192
00:16:18,560 --> 00:16:21,598
<i>to my crewmates and to NASA.</i>

193
00:16:22,080 --> 00:16:24,720
<i>And to the entire world,
really, so...</i>

194
00:16:27,720 --> 00:16:29,234
<i>Surprise.</i>

195
00:16:30,560 --> 00:16:32,950
<i>I did not die on Sol 18.</i>

196
00:16:33,120 --> 00:16:34,793
<i>Best I can figure...</i>

197
00:16:34,960 --> 00:16:37,316
<i>this length of our primary
communications antenna</i>

198
00:16:37,400 --> 00:16:38,470
<i>broke off...</i>

199
00:16:38,680 --> 00:16:40,831
<i>and tore through
my bio-monitor...</i>

200
00:16:41,000 --> 00:16:43,390
<i>and ripped a hole in me as well.</i>

201
00:16:44,240 --> 00:16:47,358
<i>But the antenna
and the blood, really,</i>

202
00:16:47,440 --> 00:16:49,477
<i>managed to seal the breach
in my suit...</i>

203
00:16:49,640 --> 00:16:51,074
<i>which kept me alive,</i>

204
00:16:51,160 --> 00:16:53,595
<i>even though the crew
must have thought I was dead.</i>

205
00:16:54,440 --> 00:16:56,750
<i>I have no way to contact NASA.</i>

206
00:16:56,920 --> 00:16:59,913
<i>And even if I could,
it's gonna be four years...</i>

207
00:17:00,120 --> 00:17:02,430
<i>until a manned mission
can reach me.</i>

208
00:17:03,440 --> 00:17:05,671
<i>And I'm in a Hab designed
to last 31 days.</i>

209
00:17:05,840 --> 00:17:08,196
<i>If the oxygenator breaks,
I'm gonna suffocate.</i>

210
00:17:08,360 --> 00:17:10,636
<i>If the water reclaimer breaks,
I'll die of thirst.</i>

211
00:17:10,840 --> 00:17:13,196
<i>If the Hab breaches,
I'm just gonna, kind of...</i>

212
00:17:13,360 --> 00:17:14,430
<i>implode.</i>

213
00:17:15,600 --> 00:17:18,354
<i>And if by some miracle,
none of that happens...</i>

214
00:17:19,120 --> 00:17:21,237
<i>eventually I'm gonna
run out of food.</i>

215
00:17:22,880 --> 00:17:23,996
<i>So...</i>

216
00:17:25,280 --> 00:17:26,280
<i>yeah.</i>

217
00:17:30,480 --> 00:17:31,550
<i>Yeah.</i>

218
00:19:20,600 --> 00:19:22,910
I'm not gonna die here.

219
00:20:02,800 --> 00:20:04,120
32...

220
00:20:05,200 --> 00:20:06,520
33...

221
00:20:08,600 --> 00:20:09,920
34...

222
00:20:11,040 --> 00:20:12,474
35, 36.

223
00:20:12,880 --> 00:20:15,714
Sweet and sour chicken.

224
00:20:48,000 --> 00:20:49,434
What do we got?

225
00:20:55,760 --> 00:20:58,355
<i>Right, let's do the math.</i>

226
00:20:58,520 --> 00:21:01,991
<i>Our surface mission here was
supposed to last 31 sols.</i>

227
00:21:02,160 --> 00:21:03,992
<i>For redundancy, they sent
68 sols worth of food.</i>

228
00:21:04,120 --> 00:21:05,349
<i>That's for 6 people.</i>

229
00:21:05,520 --> 00:21:08,115
<i>So for just me,
that's gonna last 300 sols...</i>

230
00:21:08,280 --> 00:21:11,432
<i>which I figure I can stretch
to 400 if I ration.</i>

231
00:21:11,600 --> 00:21:14,672
<i>So I got to figure out
a way to grow</i>

232
00:21:14,760 --> 00:21:16,513
<i>three years' worth of food here.</i>

233
00:21:17,360 --> 00:21:19,352
<i>On a planet where nothing grows.</i>

234
00:21:20,360 --> 00:21:21,360
<i>Luckily...</i>

235
00:21:24,160 --> 00:21:25,196
<i>I'm a botanist.</i>

236
00:21:29,280 --> 00:21:34,036
<i>Mars will come to fear
my botany powers.</i>

237
00:22:18,880 --> 00:22:20,712
<i>Pressure stable.</i>

238
00:22:31,120 --> 00:22:32,759
<i>Staple came out.</i>

239
00:23:22,640 --> 00:23:24,279
Fuck you, Mars.

240
00:23:39,520 --> 00:23:41,000
Johanssen, Jesus.

241
00:24:31,520 --> 00:24:33,398
<i>Sunday, Monday, Happy Days</i>

242
00:24:33,480 --> 00:24:34,960
<i>Tuesday, Wednesday, Happy Days</i>

243
00:24:35,960 --> 00:24:38,316
<i>Thursday, Friday, Happy Days</i>

244
00:24:38,480 --> 00:24:40,790
<i>The weekend comes, my cycle hums</i>

245
00:24:40,880 --> 00:24:42,872
<i>Ready to race to you</i>

246
00:24:43,080 --> 00:24:45,390
<i>The problem is water.</i>

247
00:24:45,920 --> 00:24:50,915
I have created
126 square meters of soil.

248
00:24:51,080 --> 00:24:53,072
<i>But every cubic meter
of soil requires</i>

249
00:24:53,200 --> 00:24:56,159
<i>40 liters of water
to be farmable.</i>

250
00:24:56,320 --> 00:24:59,472
<i>So I gotta make
a lot more water.</i>

251
00:25:00,360 --> 00:25:02,511
