Launch, what's happening?

997
01:17:46,760 --> 01:17:48,399
Force on Iris is 7 G's.

998
01:17:48,720 --> 01:17:50,393
We've lost
readings on the probe, Flight.

999
01:17:54,240 --> 01:17:57,074
Oh, Jesus Christ.

1000
01:18:00,520 --> 01:18:01,749
We've lost it, Flight.

1001
01:18:05,680 --> 01:18:06,680
SatCon?

1002
01:18:06,840 --> 01:18:07,910
<i>No satellite acquisition</i>

1003
01:18:08,040 --> 01:18:09,110
<i>of signal.</i>

1004
01:18:12,480 --> 01:18:13,480
<i>L. O.S.</i>

1005
01:18:13,560 --> 01:18:14,596
L.O.S. here, too.

1006
01:18:15,120 --> 01:18:16,270
<i>U.S. Destroyer</i> Stockton

1007
01:18:16,360 --> 01:18:18,397
<i>reporting debris
falling from the sky.</i>

1008
01:18:18,520 --> 01:18:19,590
<i>Everyone in the LCC,</i>

1009
01:18:19,720 --> 01:18:21,200
<i>maintain your positions
at your consoles.</i>

1010
01:18:21,360 --> 01:18:23,431
GC, lock the doors.

1011
01:18:51,960 --> 01:18:53,758
<i>"Commander Lewis...</i>

1012
01:18:53,920 --> 01:18:57,550
<i>"I may need you
to do something for me.</i>

1013
01:18:59,160 --> 01:19:03,996
<i>"If I die, I need you to
check in on my parents.</i>

1014
01:19:05,160 --> 01:19:08,551
<i>"They'll wanna hear all about
our time here on Mars.</i>

1015
01:19:10,120 --> 01:19:12,112
<i>"I know that sucks.</i>

1016
01:19:12,280 --> 01:19:15,512
<i>"And it'll be hard
talking to a couple...</i>

1017
01:19:16,400 --> 01:19:18,790
<i>"about their dead son.</i>

1018
01:19:19,840 --> 01:19:21,593
"It's a lot to ask.

1019
01:19:24,000 --> 01:19:26,151
"Which is why I'm asking you.

1020
01:19:27,280 --> 01:19:29,192
<i>"I'm not giving up.</i>

1021
01:19:29,360 --> 01:19:34,355
<i>"We just need to prepare
for every outcome.</i>

1022
01:19:36,040 --> 01:19:37,997
"Please tell them...

1023
01:19:40,040 --> 01:19:41,872
"Tell them I love what I do...

1024
01:19:46,280 --> 01:19:47,600
"and I'm really good at it.

1025
01:19:50,280 --> 01:19:53,318
<i>"And that I'm dying...</i>

1026
01:19:54,640 --> 01:19:57,109
"for something big...

1027
01:19:58,680 --> 01:20:00,717
"and beautiful...

1028
01:20:04,680 --> 01:20:06,717
"and greater than me.

1029
01:20:08,560 --> 01:20:11,200
<i>"Tell them
I said I can live with that.</i>

1030
01:20:12,240 --> 01:20:13,879
<i>"And tell them...</i>

1031
01:20:15,080 --> 01:20:18,676
<i>"thank you for being
my mom and dad."</i>

1032
01:20:22,320 --> 01:20:23,320
<i>We substituted protein cubes</i>

1033
01:20:23,400 --> 01:20:24,470
<i>for the standard rations.</i>

1034
01:20:24,640 --> 01:20:26,393
<i>The thrust
of the launch combined</i>

1035
01:20:26,480 --> 01:20:28,199
<i>with the simultaneous
lateral vibration...</i>

1036
01:20:28,360 --> 01:20:33,151
<i>liquefied the cubes and
created an unbalanced load.</i>

1037
01:20:33,240 --> 01:20:34,594
<i>Vincent, why wasn't
this addressed</i>

1038
01:20:34,720 --> 01:20:36,234
<i>in the inspections phase?</i>

1039
01:20:36,400 --> 01:20:37,914
<i>In order to make
our launch window,</i>

1040
01:20:38,040 --> 01:20:39,997
<i>we were forced
to accelerate our schedule.</i>

1041
01:20:41,920 --> 01:20:43,991
Their astronaut is going to die.

1042
01:20:45,880 --> 01:20:47,872
Of course there
are other ways...

1043
01:20:50,000 --> 01:20:52,754
...the Taiyang Shen booster.
Our engineers have run the numbers,

1044
01:20:53,000 --> 01:20:55,754
and it has enough fuel
for a Mars injection orbit.

1045
01:20:56,920 --> 01:20:58,274
Why hasn't NASA approached us?

1046
01:20:58,680 --> 01:20:59,750
They don't know.

1047
01:21:00,280 --> 01:21:02,715
Our booster technology
is classified.

1048
01:21:05,360 --> 01:21:08,273
So if we do nothing...

1049
01:21:08,920 --> 01:21:12,960
The world would never know
we could have helped.

1050
01:21:14,040 --> 01:21:18,876
Then, for the sake of argument,
let's say we decide to help them...

1051
01:21:19,560 --> 01:21:23,474
We'd be giving up a booster and
effectively cancelling Taiyang Shen.

1052
01:21:24,560 --> 01:21:29,635
We need to keep this among scientists,
a co-operation between space agencies.

1053
01:21:32,480 --> 01:21:33,480
Yes.

1054
01:21:34,960 --> 01:21:36,713
Yes, I understand.

1055
01:21:39,880 --> 01:21:41,109
Thank you.

1056
01:21:44,720 --> 01:21:45,790
Yes!

1057
01:21:47,160 --> 01:21:48,160
<i>All right.</i>

1058
01:21:48,280 --> 01:21:49,919
Thanks to my uncle Tommy
in China,

1059
01:21:50,000 --> 01:21:51,832
we get another chance at this.

1060
01:21:52,000 --> 01:21:55,072
Now, we finished
the <i>Iris</i> probe in 62 days.

1061
01:21:55,240 --> 01:21:58,631
We are now gonna attempt
to finish it in 28.

1062
01:22:24,320 --> 01:22:25,595
We can jettison
any kind of landing system.

1063
01:22:25,680 --> 01:22:27,114
We're only sending rations.

1064
01:22:27,280 --> 01:22:28,953
We can crash-land on Mars.

1065
01:22:30,320 --> 01:22:31,640
You should hang up the phone.

1066
01:22:32,000 --> 01:22:33,957
I'm sorry, who are you?
My name is Rich Purnell.

1067
01:22:34,120 --> 01:22:35,120
I work in Astrodynamics,

1068
01:22:35,200 --> 01:22:36,350
and you should hang up
the phone right now.

1069
01:22:38,640 --> 01:22:39,676
All right, all right.

1070
01:22:40,440 --> 01:22:41,840
I'm gonna call you back.

1071
01:22:43,160 --> 01:22:44,640
I know how to save Mark Watney.

1072
01:22:45,880 --> 01:22:48,190
Your probe plan won't work.
Too many things can go wrong.

1073
01:22:48,560 --> 01:22:49,560
I've got a better way.

1074
01:22:49,720 --> 01:22:50,790
Astrodynamics?

1075
01:22:50,960 --> 01:22:52,314
Yeah.

1076
01:22:52,720 --> 01:22:55,235
What the hell
is "Project Elrond"?

1077
01:22:55,640 --> 01:22:56,640
I had to make something up.

1078
01:22:56,800 --> 01:22:58,234
But "Elrond"?

1079
01:22:58,720 --> 01:23:00,712
Because it's a secret meeting.

1080
01:23:00,880 --> 01:23:01,880
How do you know that?

1081
01:23:01,960 --> 01:23:03,394
Why does "Elrond" mean
"secret meeting"?

1082
01:23:03,560 --> 01:23:06,155
<i>The Council of Elrond.
It's from</i> Lord of the Rings.

1083
01:23:06,320 --> 01:23:07,356
<i>Lord of the Rings.</i>

1084
01:23:07,440 --> 01:23:08,476
It's the meeting
where they decide

1085
01:23:08,560 --> 01:23:09,630
to destroy the One Ring.

1086
01:23:09,720 --> 01:23:11,393
<i>If we're gonna call
something "Project Elrond"...</i>

1087
01:23:11,560 --> 01:23:13,711
I would like my code name
to be "Glorfindel."

1088
01:23:13,920 --> 01:23:15,912
Okay, I hate every one of you.

1089
01:23:16,080 --> 01:23:18,436
What, Teddy doesn't even
know about this yet?

1090
01:23:18,600 --> 01:23:19,750
I'm sorry, who are you?

1091
01:23:19,920 --> 01:23:21,639
This is Rich Purnell,
Astrodynamics.

1092
01:23:22,760 --> 01:23:24,240
Tell them what you just told me.

1093
01:23:24,520 --> 01:23:27,513
I can get the <i>Hermes</i>
back to Mars by Sol 561.

1094
01:23:29,240 --> 01:23:30,240
How?

1095
01:23:34,440 --> 01:23:37,080
Could you stand right
there for me, please?

1096
01:23:38,760 --> 01:23:39,760
Thanks.

1097
01:23:39,920 --> 01:23:40,990
Right there. Great.

1098
01:23:41,200 --> 01:23:45,353
And could you stand
right there? Right there.

1099
01:23:50,120 --> 01:23:53,875
Okay, let's pretend that this
stapler is the <i>Hermes...</i>

1100
01:23:54,040 --> 01:23:56,271
and you are...

1101
01:23:56,440 --> 01:23:57,590
I'm sorry,
what's your name again?

1102
01:23:57,840 --> 01:24:01,197
Teddy. I'm the Director
of NASA.

1103
01:24:01,520 --> 01:24:03,477
Cool. Teddy,
you're Earth.

1104
01:24:03,840 --> 01:24:06,116
And right now, the <i>Hermes</i>
is headed towards you...

1105
01:24:06,280 --> 01:24:08,715
starting its month-long
deceleration to intercept.

1106
01:24:08,880 --> 01:24:11,395
But instead,
what I'm proposing is...

1107
01:24:15,480 --> 01:24:17,597
we start accelerating
immediately

1108
01:24:17,680 --> 01:24:19,478
to preserve velocity
and gain even more.

1109
01:24:19,640 --> 01:24:20,710
We don't intercept
with Earth at all...

1110
01:24:20,880 --> 01:24:22,200
but we come close enough

1111
01:24:22,320 --> 01:24:24,471
to get a gravity assist
and adjust course.

1112
01:24:24,640 --> 01:24:26,472
While we're doing that...

1113
01:24:28,640 --> 01:24:30,313
we resupply with the probe...

1114
01:24:30,480 --> 01:24:31,480
The <i>Taiyang Shen.</i>

1115
01:24:31,640 --> 01:24:33,199
...pick up whatever
provisions we need...

1116
01:24:33,360 --> 01:24:35,511
and now we're accelerating
towards Mars.

1117
01:24:38,160 --> 01:24:39,480
You're Mars.

1118
01:24:39,640 --> 01:24:40,710
Now, we're going too fast

1119
01:24:40,840 --> 01:24:42,559
at this point to fall
into orbit...

1120
01:24:42,760 --> 01:24:44,080
but we can do a flyby.

1121
01:24:44,240 --> 01:24:45,240
<i>What good is a flyby</i>

1122
01:24:45,320 --> 01:24:46,720
<i>if we can't get Watney
off the surface?</i>

1123
01:24:47,320 --> 01:24:50,154
Watney would intercept
using the MAV.

1124
01:24:50,240 --> 01:24:51,310
Ow!

1125
01:24:54,920 --> 01:24:56,877
And then we just head home.

1126
01:25:01,360 --> 01:25:03,670
I've done the math.
It checks out.

1127
01:25:05,440 --> 01:25:06,920
<i>Rich.
Yes, sir.</i>

1128
01:25:07,000 --> 01:25:08,036
Get out.

1129
01:25:08,120 --> 01:25:09,120
All right.

1130
01:25:15,520 --> 01:25:17,239
- Is he right?
- Yeah.

1131
01:25:17,560 --> 01:25:19,517
Bruce, what do you think?

1132
01:25:20,120 --> 01:25:21,600
<i>Well, if Vincent says so.</i>

1133
01:25:23,040 --> 01:25:25,236
We need to use the <i>Taiyang Shen?</i>

1134
01:25:25,360 --> 01:25:26,360
Uh-huh.

1135
01:25:26,600 --> 01:25:28,557
What am I missing?
Why is that important?

1136
01:25:28,720 --> 01:25:29,949
Because we can only do one.

1137
01:25:30,120 --> 01:25:32,271
Send Watney enough food
to last till <i>Ares 4...</i>

1138
01:25:32,480 --> 01:25:34,358
or send <i>Hermes</i> back
to get him right now.

1139
01:25:35,040 --> 01:25:36,235
Both plans require
the <i>Taiyang Shen,</i>

1140
01:25:36,400 --> 01:25:38,198
so we have to choose.

1141
01:25:38,560 --> 01:25:40,074
But what about the <i>Hermes</i> crew?

1142
01:25:40,280 --> 01:25:41,839
We'd be asking them to add

1143
01:25:41,920 --> 01:25:45,038
533 extra days to their mission.

1144
01:25:45,400 --> 01:25:47,119
Yeah. They wouldn't hesitate,
not for a second.

1145
01:25:48,240 --> 01:25:49,913
Can the <i>Hermes</i> function
for 533 days

1146
01:25:50,080 --> 01:25:51,275
beyond the scheduled
mission end?

1147
01:25:51,400 --> 01:25:52,400
It should.

1148
01:25:52,560 --> 01:25:54,392
Built to last
the full <i>Ares</i> mission...

1149
01:25:54,560 --> 01:25:56,631
so technically, it's only
halfway through its lifespan.

1150
01:25:57,400 --> 01:25:58,550
But if something goes wrong...

1151
01:25:58,720 --> 01:26:00,120
Then we lose the crew.

1152
01:26:00,400 --> 01:26:01,993
<i>So what?
We either have a high chance</i>

1153
01:26:02,120 --> 01:26:03,839
<i>of killing one person...</i>

1154
01:26:04,120 --> 01:26:06,555
<i>or a low chance
of killing six people.</i>

1155
01:26:06,760 --> 01:26:08,080
<i>How do we make that decision?</i>

1156
01:26:08,240 --> 01:26:10,072
We don't have to make it, Bruce.

1157
01:26:10,160 --> 01:26:11,160
He does.

1158
01:26:11,600 --> 01:26:12,636
Yeah, well, bullshit.

1159
01:26:13,120 --> 01:26:14,998
It should be
Commander Lewis' call.

1160
01:26:15,160 --> 01:26:16,719
We still have a chance to bring

1161
01:26:16,800 --> 01:26:18,439
five astronauts
home safe and sound.

1162
01:26:18,600 --> 01:26:20,159
I'm not risking their lives.

1163
01:26:21,320 --> 01:26:22,959
Let them make that decision.

1164
01:26:23,680 --> 01:26:26,354
Mitch, we're going
with option one.

1165
01:26:28,280 --> 01:26:30,272
You goddamn coward.

1166
01:26:48,480 --> 01:26:50,437
<i>Johanssen?
Yeah.</i>

1167
01:26:51,160 --> 01:26:53,675
I know it's your private time.
Can I bother you for a second?

1168
01:26:53,800 --> 01:26:54,800
<i>Yeah, go ahead.</i>

1169
01:26:54,920 --> 01:26:55,920
<i>Where are you?</i>

1170
01:26:55,960 --> 01:26:56,960
The gym.

1171
01:27:18,800 --> 01:27:20,029
What's up?

1172
01:27:20,200 --> 01:27:21,200
I just got an email from my wife

1173
01:27:21,320 --> 01:27:24,233
and the subject line
says, "Our children."

1174
01:27:24,560 --> 01:27:26,552
My computer won't open
the attachment.

1175
01:27:28,000 --> 01:27:29,195
Okay.

1176
01:27:29,360 --> 01:27:30,476
Let's take a look.

1177
01:27:34,400 --> 01:27:35,550
Uh...

1178
01:27:37,000 --> 01:27:38,000
Let's see.

1179
01:27:40,320 --> 01:27:42,357
This isn't a JPEG.

1180
01:27:42,720 --> 01:27:45,155
It's a plain ASCII text file.

1181
01:27:48,000 --> 01:27:49,275
I don't really know
what we're looking at.

1182
01:27:51,000 --> 01:27:52,354
Does that make any sense to you?

1183
01:27:54,680 --> 01:27:56,831
"Rich Purnell Maneuver."

1184
01:27:57,040 --> 01:27:59,839
It's a course maneuver
for the <i>Hermes.</i>

1185
01:28:06,880 --> 01:28:08,075
And the mission concludes
with Earth intercept,

1186
01:28:08,200 --> 01:28:09,200
211 days later.

1187
01:28:10,560 --> 01:28:11,960
Would it work?

1188
01:28:12,200 --> 01:28:14,192
Mmm-hmm. We ran
the numbers. They check out.

1189
01:28:14,360 --> 01:28:15,794
It's a brilliant course.

1190
01:28:15,920 --> 01:28:18,754
So why all the cloak and dagger?

1191
01:28:18,920 --> 01:28:20,718
Because it goes directly
against NASA's decision.

1192
01:28:20,880 --> 01:28:22,837
Yeah. If we do
the maneuver,

1193
01:28:22,920 --> 01:28:25,037
they'd have to send
the supply ship or we die.

1194
01:28:25,200 --> 01:28:28,432
We have the opportunity
to force their hand.

1195
01:28:29,600 --> 01:28:31,910
So, are we gonna do it?

1196
01:28:33,280 --> 01:28:35,237
If it was up to me,
we'd already be on our way.

1197
01:28:35,400 --> 01:28:37,471
But it is, though,
isn't it? Up to you.

1198
01:28:38,080 --> 01:28:39,150
Not this time.

1199
01:28:39,320 --> 01:28:42,279
This is something NASA
expressly rejected.

1200
01:28:43,120 --> 01:28:44,873
We're talking about mutiny here,

1201
01:28:44,960 --> 01:28:46,394
which is not a word
that I take lightly.

1202
01:28:46,560 --> 01:28:49,120
So we do this together
or not at all.

1203
01:28:49,280 --> 01:28:52,239
And before you answer,
consider the consequences.

1204
01:28:52,400 --> 01:28:55,438
If we mess up the supply
rendezvous, we die.

1205
01:28:55,640 --> 01:28:58,394
If we mess up the Earth
gravity assist, we die.

1206
01:28:58,600 --> 01:29:01,638
If we do everything perfectly...

1207
01:29:01,800 --> 01:29:04,918
we add 533 days to our mission.

1208
01:29:05,080 --> 01:29:08,960
533 more days before
we see our families again.

1209
01:29:09,120 --> 01:29:13,637
533 days of unplanned
space travel...

1210
01:29:13,800 --> 01:29:15,359
where anything could go wrong.

1211
01:29:15,520 --> 01:29:18,911
If it's mission
critical, we die.

1212
01:29:19,760 --> 01:29:20,796
Sign me up.

1213
01:29:21,000 --> 01:29:22,434
All right, cowboy, slow down.

1214
01:29:22,600 --> 01:29:24,273
You and I, we're military.

1215
01:29:24,440 --> 01:29:26,113
Chances are, we go home,
they'll court martial us.

1216
01:29:26,200 --> 01:29:27,200
Yeah, there's that.

1217
01:29:27,280 --> 01:29:28,396
And for the rest of you guys...

1218
01:29:28,480 --> 01:29:31,393
I guarantee they will never
send you back up here again.

1219
01:29:31,480 --> 01:29:35,952
Good. So, if we go
for it, how would it work?

1220
01:29:36,120 --> 01:29:37,679
I plot the course
and execute it.

1221
01:29:37,840 --> 01:29:39,115
Remote override.

1222
01:29:39,280 --> 01:29:40,430
They could take over the <i>Hermes</i>

1223
01:29:40,560 --> 01:29:41,789
from Mission Control.

1224
01:29:43,000 --> 01:29:44,957
Can you disable it?

1225
01:29:45,120 --> 01:29:47,191
<i>Hermes</i> has four redundant
flight computers...

1226
01:29:47,400 --> 01:29:49,676
each connected to three
redundant comm systems.

1227
01:29:49,840 --> 01:29:51,069
We can't shut down the comms

1228
01:29:51,160 --> 01:29:52,674
because we'd lose
telemetry and guidance.

1229
01:29:52,840 --> 01:29:54,399
And we can't shut down
the computers

1230
01:29:54,480 --> 01:29:56,153
because we need to run the ship.

1231
01:29:56,320 --> 01:29:59,631
I'd have to disable remote
override on each system.

1232
01:29:59,800 --> 01:30:01,712
It's part of the OS, I'd have
to jump over the code.

1233
01:30:01,880 --> 01:30:04,520
Okay, but, like, in English,
what would that mean?

1234
01:30:06,560 --> 01:30:07,789
I can do it.

1235
01:30:08,840 --> 01:30:09,876
Great.

1236
01:30:11,520 --> 01:30:13,034
Well, it has to be unanimous.

1237
01:30:13,840 --> 01:30:18,471
If we do this, it'll be
over 900 days of space.

1238
01:30:20,840 --> 01:30:24,231
That's more than enough
space for one life...

1239
01:30:25,080 --> 01:30:26,309
so, yes.

1240
01:30:26,840 --> 01:30:28,194
I vote yes.

1241
01:30:30,520 --> 01:30:32,034
Let's go get him.

1242
01:30:34,920 --> 01:30:35,920
Johanssen?

